    <!-- Section 10: Military Families in South Carolina -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <SectionHeading title="Military Families in South Carolina" accent />
      <div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="leading-relaxed">South Carolina is home to a significant military community, anchored by Joint Base Charleston and Fort Jackson &mdash; the U.S. Army's largest and most active Initial Entry Training center. The state also hosts Shaw Air Force Base, the Marine Corps Recruit Depot at Parris Island, and the Marine Corps Air Station Beaufort. Tens of thousands of active-duty service members, veterans, and military families call South Carolina home.</p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">Many military families assume that VA burial benefits will fully cover funeral costs. In reality, VA benefits are modest: the current burial allowance ranges from approximately $300 for non-service-connected deaths to around $2,000 for service-connected deaths. Veterans buried in VA national cemeteries receive a gravesite, opening and closing of the grave, and a headstone at no charge, but the family is still responsible for the funeral service, transportation, casket or urn, embalming, and all professional fees.</p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">For a traditional funeral costing $8,000 or more, VA benefits cover only a fraction of the total expense. This gap is where preneed insurance becomes essential for military families. A well-structured preneed plan works alongside VA benefits to ensure full coverage, so your family never faces an unexpected financial burden during an already difficult time.</p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">Military families also face unique challenges with frequent relocations. If you purchase a preneed plan in South Carolina and later move to another state, insurance-funded plans travel with you &mdash; the policy can be reassigned to a funeral home in your new location. This portability makes insurance-funded preneed especially well-suited to the military lifestyle.</p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">For a complete breakdown of what VA benefits do and do not cover, visit our <a href="/learn/va-funeral-benefits" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">guide to VA funeral benefits</a>. If you are stationed at or retired from a South Carolina installation, I am available to meet at your convenience &mdash; call <a href={`tel:${PHONE_RAW}`} class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">{PHONE}</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 11: FAQ -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <SectionHeading title="Frequently Asked Questions" accent />
      <div class="space-y-4 mt-6">

        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border-light bg-white overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-5 text-charcoal-900 font-heading font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-linen/50 transition-colors">
            Is preneed insurance required in South Carolina?
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-charcoal-400 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-charcoal-500 leading-relaxed">No. Preneed insurance is entirely voluntary in South Carolina. However, SC law (SC Code &sect; 32-7) does require that any preneed seller be properly licensed and that all funds collected be placed in trust or backed by an insurance policy. You are never obligated to purchase a preneed plan, but if you choose to, the state ensures strong consumer protections are in place.</div>
        </details>

        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border-light bg-white overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-5 text-charcoal-900 font-heading font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-linen/50 transition-colors">
            Can I transfer my SC preneed plan to another funeral home?
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-charcoal-400 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-charcoal-500 leading-relaxed">Yes. South Carolina law protects your right to transfer a preneed contract to another licensed funeral home within the state. If you move or simply change your preference, you can request a transfer. The original provider must release the funds &mdash; either from the trust or the insurance assignment &mdash; to the new funeral home. There may be administrative fees, but the core value of your plan is protected.</div>
        </details>

        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border-light bg-white overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-5 text-charcoal-900 font-heading font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-linen/50 transition-colors">
            How is SC preneed different from NC preneed?
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-charcoal-400 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-charcoal-500 leading-relaxed">Both states require preneed funds to be protected through trust accounts or insurance policies, and both states exempt irrevocable preneed plans from Medicaid asset calculations. The key differences are in the regulatory bodies (SC Board of Funeral Service vs NC Board of Funeral Service), licensing fees ($250 in SC vs $50,000 surety bond + $150 in NC), and specific consumer protection statutes. Duane Cutlip is licensed in both states, so he can guide families through either state's requirements. See our <a href="/learn/preneed-insurance-nc" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">NC preneed guide</a> for a detailed comparison.</div>
        </details>

        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border-light bg-white overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-5 text-charcoal-900 font-heading font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-linen/50 transition-colors">
            Does preneed insurance affect Medicaid eligibility in SC?
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-charcoal-400 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-charcoal-500 leading-relaxed">An irrevocable preneed insurance plan is exempt from Medicaid asset calculations in South Carolina. This means the funds set aside for your funeral are not counted when determining Medicaid eligibility. This is one of the most important planning tools available to SC families who may need long-term care coverage. However, the plan must be irrevocable &mdash; meaning you give up the right to cancel or access its cash value &mdash; for the Medicaid exemption to apply. Learn more in our <a href="/learn/medicaid-funeral-planning" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">Medicaid funeral planning guide</a>.</div>
        </details>

        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border-light bg-white overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-5 text-charcoal-900 font-heading font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-linen/50 transition-colors">
            Can someone licensed in NC sell preneed in SC?
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-charcoal-400 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-charcoal-500 leading-relaxed">Not automatically. Each state has its own licensing requirements. A preneed agent must hold a valid license in the state where they are selling. Duane Cutlip holds licenses in both North Carolina and South Carolina, allowing him to serve families across both states. If you work with an agent who is only licensed in one state, they cannot legally sell preneed plans in the other.</div>
        </details>

        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border-light bg-white overflow-hidden">
          <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-5 text-charcoal-900 font-heading font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-linen/50 transition-colors">
            What happens if the funeral home I chose goes out of business?
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-charcoal-400 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-charcoal-500 leading-relaxed">Your preneed funds are protected under SC law regardless of what happens to the funeral home. If your plan is insurance-funded, the insurance policy remains valid and can be assigned to any other licensed funeral home. If your plan is trust-funded, the funds held in trust are protected from the funeral home's creditors and can be transferred. The SC Board of Funeral Service oversees these situations to ensure consumers are not harmed.</div>
        </details>

      </div>
    </section>

